			<div class="blogComment">
				&nbsp;<br /><a name="112854062837716169"></a> 
				Well, the languages that were mentioned in the article that led to my post are Python, Jython, Smalltalk and Scheme.  The other examples that spring to people's lips are Ruby and Perl. Sometimes PHP too. (ECMAscript doesn't receive many mentions, which is interesting since it's so ubiquitous.)  Erlang is not a household name, as you know.<BR/><BR/>With regard to hiring decisions, I think a lot of these choices are made by self-hired developers and people making web sites and so on.  And in a very many places, I am not sure the maturity of the organization and the hiring managers would be one where this discussion made any sense.<BR/><BR/>By another venue, I was wondering if you had a blog and we could cross link our thoughts rather than hiding out down here in the comments of a rarely-read blog.<br />
